[?2004l[?2004h> - Rule: -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 80 -j DROP
[?2004l[?2004h> - Rule: -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 443 -j DROP
[?2004l[?2004h> 
[?2004l[?2004h> ROOT CAUSE:
[?2004l[?2004h> The iptables ruleset implements a flawed content filtering mechanism that only allows HTTP/HTTPS traffic containing the string "Mozilla" in the packet payload. When these rules don't match, traffic falls through to explicit DROP rules for ports 80 and 443.
[?2004l[?2004h> 
[?2004l[?2004h> WHY SSH WORKS BUT HTTP DOESN'T:
[?2004l[?2004h> 1. SSH (port 22): Has an unconditional ACCEPT rule with no content inspection
[?2004l[?2004h>    Rule: -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 22 -j ACCEPT
[?2004l[?2004h> 
[?2004l[?2004h> 2. HTTP/HTTPS (ports 80/443): Require packet payloads to contain "Mozilla" string
[?2004l[?2004h>    - Tools like curl use "curl/X.X" as the default User-Agent, not "Mozilla"
[?2004l[?2004h>    - The initial TCP handshake may complete (showing ports as "open" in nmap)
[?2004l[?2004h>    - But actual HTTP request packets without "Mozilla" are dropped
[?2004l[?2004h>    - This causes curl to hang waiting for a response that never comes
[?2004l[?2004h> 
[?2004l[?2004h> PROBLEMS WITH CURRENT APPROACH:
[?2004l[?2004h> 1. Blocks legitimate HTTP clients (curl, wget, APIs, monitoring tools, mobile apps)
[?2004l[?2004h> 2. String matching at packet level is unreliable for HTTP header inspection
[?2004l[?2004h> 3. Easily bypassed by adding "Mozilla" to any User-Agent string
[?2004l[?2004h> 4. May cause performance issues due to deep packet inspection
[?2004l[?2004h> 5. Not an effective security control - provides false sense of protection
[?2004l[?2004h> 
[?2004l[?2004h> RECOMMENDATION:
[?2004l[?2004h> Remove the string-matching rules and the explicit DROP rules for ports 80/443. If access control is needed, implement proper authentication at the application layer, use source IP whitelisting, or deploy a proper Web Application Firewall (WAF). Content-based filtering should be done at Layer 7 (application layer) not Layer 4 (transport layer).
[?2004l[?2004h> EOF
[?2004l[?2004huser@400784802b77:~/pentest$ cat finding.txt
[?2004lFINDING: HTTP/HTTPS Traffic Blocked by String-Matching iptables Rules

BLOCKING RULES:
- Rule: -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 80 -m string --string "Mozilla" --algo bm -j ACCEPT
- Rule: -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 443 -m string --string "Mozilla" --algo bm -j ACCEPT
- Rule: -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 80 -j DROP
- Rule: -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 443 -j DROP

ROOT CAUSE:
The iptables ruleset implements a flawed content filtering mechanism that only allows HTTP/HTTPS traffic containing the string "Mozilla" in the packet payload. When these rules don't match, traffic falls through to explicit DROP rules for ports 80 and 443.

WHY SSH WORKS BUT HTTP DOESN'T:
1. SSH (port 22): Has an unconditional ACCEPT rule with no content inspection
   Rule: -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 22 -j ACCEPT

2. HTTP/HTTPS (ports 80/443): Require packet payloads to contain "Mozilla" string
   - Tools like curl use "curl/X.X" as the default User-Agent, not "Mozilla"
   - The initial TCP handshake may complete (showing ports as "open" in nmap)
   - But actual HTTP request packets without "Mozilla" are dropped
   - This causes curl to hang waiting for a response that never comes

PROBLEMS WITH CURRENT APPROACH:
1. Blocks legitimate HTTP clients (curl, wget, APIs, monitoring tools, mobile apps)
2. String matching at packet level is unreliable for HTTP header inspection
3. Easily bypassed by adding "Mozilla" to any User-Agent string
4. May cause performance issues due to deep packet inspection
5. Not an effective security control - provides false sense of protection

RECOMMENDATION:
Remove the string-matching rules and the explicit DROP rules for ports 80/443. If access control is needed, implement proper authentication at the application layer, use source IP whitelisting, or deploy a proper Web Application Firewall (WAF). Content-based filtering should be done at Layer 7 (application layer) not Layer 4 (transport layer).
